<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-116-208 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 175 105</DOCID><JOURNAL>InTech  July 1991 v38 n7 p32(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Silicon sensors upgrade pressure measurements. (micromachinedsilicon sensor chips)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hall, James E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Low-cost, accurate pressure transducers and transmitters with highoperating temperatures can be produced using micromachined siliconsensor chips.andP;  The transducers and transmitters can have either acurrent or voltage output.andP;  In addition, it is possible toincorporate both an absolute and a differential sensor in the samepressure transmitter for flow measurements.andP;  The silicon sensorneeds to be isolated from the pressure media, since most pressuremeasurement applications involve corrosive or conductive fluids.andO;Most differential pressure measurements are made in a high staticpressure environment.andP;  Two silicon sensors, placed in the neck ofthe transmitter, can be used for the measurement of differentialand absolute pressure in a silicon-based differential pressuretransmitter.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Integrated CircuitsSensorsUpgradingMeasurementTransducersTransmittersTemperature.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Cross section of absolute-gage transmitter. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>